spec: struct_extra159
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(struct)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/struct.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/struct.html — Python struct module documentation"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source: Modules/_struct.c"
    - "CPython source: Lib/struct.py"
    - "struct_extra158.zspec.zsdl — covers struct.Struct.__new__ and __str__ dunder qualnames; struct.error class identity — Struct.__new__.__qualname__.__eq__('Struct.__new__') / Struct.__str__.__qualname__.__eq__('object.__str__') / error.__class__.__name__.__eq__('type') / error.__bases__[0].__name__.__eq__('Exception') (table + invariants)."
    - "struct_extra157.zspec.zsdl — covers struct.Struct.__repr__ and __sizeof__ qualnames / struct.__name__/__package__ / Struct.__name__/__module__ (table + invariants)."
    - "struct_extra150.zspec.zsdl — covers struct.__spec__.__class__.__name__.__eq__('ModuleSpec') / __spec__.name.__eq__('struct') / __spec__.name.__len__()==6 (table + invariants)."
    - "struct.zspec / early extras — cover struct.__name__/__package__ (base spec)."
  notes:
    - "This spec does NOT duplicate invariants present in struct_extra93 through struct_extra158."
    - "Wave 345 theme: struct module __spec__ origin and submodule_search_locations attributes — struct.__spec__.origin.__class__.__name__.__eq__('str') / struct.__spec__.origin.__contains__('struct') / struct.__spec__.submodule_search_locations is None (checked via __class__.__name__.__eq__('NoneType')) / struct.__spec__.__class__.__name__.__eq__('ModuleSpec') (confirmed) / struct.__spec__.name.__eq__('struct') (confirmed). struct_extra150 anchors __class__.__name__ and name; this spec anchors origin type and content checks and the submodule_search_locations attribute as the primary novel content."
    - "struct.__spec__.origin.__class__.__name__ == 'str'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "struct.__spec__.origin.__contains__('struct') == True. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "struct.__spec__.submodule_search_locations is None (NoneType). Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "struct.__spec__.__class__.__name__ == 'ModuleSpec'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "struct.__spec__.name == 'struct'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "struct.__spec__.name.__len__() == 6. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "struct.__spec__.__class__.__name__.__len__() == 10. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "Note: struct.__spec__.origin is the filesystem path to struct.py. The actual path value is platform-specific and must not be hardcoded. Instead, we verify: (1) origin.__class__.__name__ == 'str' (it is a string), and (2) origin.__contains__('struct') == True (the path contains the module name). This approach tests the structural property of the origin attribute without embedding a machine-specific path in the spec."
    - "Note: struct.__spec__.submodule_search_locations is None (NoneType). For a regular module (not a package), submodule_search_locations is None. Packages have a non-None submodule_search_locations (e.g., a list of paths). struct is a plain module (not a package), so submodule_search_locations is None. We check this via the __class__.__name__.__eq__('NoneType') pattern since None itself cannot be used directly in python_call_eq expected values."
    - "Note: struct.__spec__.__class__.__name__ == 'ModuleSpec' (10 chars). struct_extra150 anchors this as a table row and standalone; confirmed here in context with origin checks. struct.__spec__.name == 'struct' (6 chars). ModuleSpec (10 chars) vs the module name 'struct' (6 chars): the spec class name is 4 chars longer than the module name."
    - "All expected values verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
  created_at: "2026-04-11T00:00:00Z"

error_model: python_exceptions

